===Verb===
{{en-verb|slides|sliding|slid}}

# {{context|ergative|lang=en}} To (cause to) move in continuous contact with a surface
#: ''He '''slid''' the boat across the grass.''
#: ''The safe '''slid''' slowly.''
#: ''Snow '''slides''' down the side of a mountain.''
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To move on a low-friction surface.
#: ''The car '''slid''' on the ice.''
#* Waller
#*: They bathe in summer, and in winter '''slide'''.
# {{context|intransitive|baseball|lang=en}} To drop down and skid into a base.
#: ''Jones '''slid''' into second.''
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To lose one’s balance on a slippery surface.
#: ''He '''slid''' while going around the corner.''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To pass or put imperceptibly; to slip.
#: ''to '''slide''' in a word to vary the sense of a question''
# {{cx|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To pass inadvertently.
#* Bible, Eccles. xxviii. 26
#*: Beware thou '''slide''' not by it.
# {{cx|intransitive|lang=en}} To pass along smoothly or unobservedly; to move gently onward without friction or hindrance.
#: ''A ship or boat '''slides''' through the water.''
#* Dryden
#*: Ages shall '''slide''' away without perceiving.
#* Alexander Pope
#*: Parts answering parts shall '''slide''' into a whole.
# {{cx|music|lang=en}} To pass from one note to another with no perceptible cessation of sound.
# To pass out of one's thought as not being of any consequence.
#* Chaucer
#*: With good hope let he sorrow '''slide'''.
#* Sir Philip Sidney
#*: With a calm carelessness letting everything '''slide'''.

